# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pygame
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:pygame/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Professional game development usually begins with a game design, which itself has several possible origins.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Occasionally the game development process starts with no clear design in mind, but as a series of experiments.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, game designer Will Wright began development of *The Sims* by getting programmers to experiment with several ideas.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Programmers are often required to produce prototypes of gameplay ideas and features.
[src:pygame/game-programming] A great deal of prototyping may take place during pre-production, before the design document is complete, and may help determine what features the design specifies.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Prototypes are developed quickly with very little time for up-front design and mostly act as a proof of concept or to test ideas.
[src:pygame/game-programming] They are not expected to work flawlessly, but are developed to try out new, sometimes exotic, ideas.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Though the programmer's main job is not to develop the game design, the programmers often contribute to the design, as do game artists.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The game designer will solicit input from both the producer and the art and programming lead for ideas and strategies for the game design.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Often individuals in non-lead positions also contribute, such as copywriters and other programmers and artists.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Programmers often closely follow the game design document.
[src:pygame/game-programming] As the game development progresses, the design document changes as programming limitations and new capabilities are discovered and exploited.
[src:pygame/game-programming] During production, programmers may create a great deal of source code to create the game described in the game's design document.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Along the way, the design document is modified to meet limitations or expanded to exploit new features.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The design document is very much a "living document", much of whose life is dictated by programmer's schedules, talent and resourcefulness.
[src:pygame/game-programming] While many programmers have some say in a game's content, most game producers solicit input from the lead programmer as to the status of a game programming development.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The lead is responsible for knowing the status of all facets of the game's programming and for pointing out limitations.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The lead programmer may also pass on suggestions from the programmers as to possible features they'd like to implement.
[src:pygame/game-programming] With today's visually rich content, the programmer must often interact with the art staff.
[src:pygame/game-programming] This very much depends on the programmer's role, of course.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, a 3D graphics programmer may need to work side by side with the game's 3D modelers discussing strategies and design considerations, while an AI programmer may need to interact very little, if at all, with the art staff.
[src:pygame/game-programming] To help artists and level designers with their tasks, programmers may volunteer or be called upon to develop tools and utilities.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Many of these may be for a specific purpose and can be buggy due to time constraints (time for development of such tools is often not included in a game's schedule) as well as because they are only for in-house use anyway.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Many game tools are developed in RAD languages for quicker development and may be discarded after the completion of the game.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The formal quality assurance testing process, performed by professional game testers, begins well into game development.
[src:pygame/game-programming] High-budget titles may begin testing with the first playable alpha, while low-budget and casual games might not enter testing until a release candidate is ready.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The programmers' task is to fix errors and bugs as such are discovered by the QA teams.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Final tasks include "polishing" the game, such as programmers fixing occasional bugs—from minor to catastrophic—that may arise during the last phases of testing.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Game developers may have a beta testing period, but the definition of such varies from developer to developer.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Often a beta contains all of the game's features, but may have a few bugs or incomplete content.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Few games are given a public beta period, for example, to measure stress tolerance for game servers.
[src:pygame/game-programming] When the game is deemed complete, it is said to have "gone gold" and is shipped off to the publisher.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Depending on circumstances, the publisher may then subject it to its own quality assurance or may begin pressing the game from the gold master.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Once a game ships, the maintenance phase for the video game begins.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Programmers wait for a period to get as many bug reports as possible.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Once the developer thinks they've obtained enough feedback, the programmers start working on a patch.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The patch may take weeks or months to develop, but it's intended to fix most bugs and problems with the game.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Occasionally a patch may include extra features or content or may even alter gameplay.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Most modern games take from one to three years to complete.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The length of development depends on a number of factors, but programming is required throughout all phases of development except the very early stages of game design.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Like other software, game development programs are generated from source code to the actual program (called the *executable*) by a compiler.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Source code can be developed with almost any text editor, but many professional game programmers use a full integrated development environment.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Once again, which IDE one uses depends on the target platform.
[src:pygame/game-programming] In addition to IDEs, many game development companies create custom tools developed to be used in-house.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some of these include prototypes and asset conversion tools (programs that change artwork, for example, into the game's custom format).
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some custom tools may even be delivered with the game, such as a level editor.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Game development companies are often very willing to spend thousands of dollars to make sure their programmers are well equipped with the best tools.
[src:pygame/game-programming] A well outfitted programmer may have two to three development systems and multiple monitors dominating their office or cubicle.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Once the game's initial design has been agreed upon, the development language must be decided upon.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The choice depends upon many factors, such as language familiarity of the programming staff, target platforms, the execution speed requirements and the language of any game engines, APIs or libraries being used.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For personal computers, the language selected may be little more than a matter of preference.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Language bindings for popular libraries such as SDL and Allegro are widespread, and the performance gap between idiomatic code written in modern compiled languages is negligible.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The most popular languages are usually procedural or object-oriented and implemented via compilers; for example, C, C++, and Java.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, developers may take into account domain-specific features, such as interfacing with the operating system, and resilience to reverse engineering for online video games.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Many games are not written in one language exclusively, and may combine two or more languages; For example, Unity, a popular game engine, has different pieces written in C, C++, and C#.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For consoles, the support of the target platform is usually the most considered factor.
[src:pygame/game-programming] In the past, video games for consoles were written almost exclusively in assembly due to limited resources in terms of both storage and processing speed.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, as technology has advanced, so have the options for game development on consoles.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Nintendo, Microsoft, and Sony all have differing SDKs for their Nintendo Switch, Xbox One, and PlayStation 4 consoles, respectively.
[src:pygame/game-programming] High-level scripting languages are increasingly being used as embedded extensions to the underlying game written in a compiled programming language, for the convenience of both the original developer and anyone who would wish to mod the game.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Lua is a very popular choice, as its API is written in ANSI C and the language is designed to be embedded into other applications.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Many developers have created custom languages altogether for their games, such as id Software's QuakeC and Epic Games' UnrealScript.
[src:pygame/game-programming] A key decision in game programming is which, if any, APIs and libraries to use.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Today, there are numerous libraries available which take care of key tasks of game programming.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some libraries can handle sound processing, input, and graphics rendering.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some can even handle some AI tasks such as pathfinding.
[src:pygame/game-programming] There are even entire game engines that handle most of the tasks of game programming and only require coding game logic.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Which APIs and libraries one chooses depends largely on the target platform.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, libraries for PlayStation 2 development may not be available for Microsoft Windows and vice versa.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, there are game frameworks available that allow or ease cross-platform development, so programmers can program a game in a single language and have the game run on several platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, PSP and Microsoft Windows.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Today, graphics are a key defining feature of most games.
[src:pygame/game-programming] While 2D graphics used to be the norm for games released through the mid-1990s, most AAA games now boast full 3D graphics, even for games which are largely 2D in nature, such as *Civilization III*.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, purely 2D graphics have experienced a Renaissance with indie games.
[src:pygame/game-programming] A well established personal computer platform is Microsoft Windows.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Since it came pre-installed on almost ninety percent of PCs sold, it now has the largest user base.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The two most popular 3D graphics APIs for Microsoft Windows are Direct3D and OpenGL.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The benefits and weaknesses of each API are hotly debated among Windows game programmers.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Currently, the most popular Computing platform is Google Android.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Since it comes pre-installed on almost eighty percent of Smartphones sold, Android has the second largest user base, and increasing.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Direct3D is freely available from Microsoft, as are the rest of the DirectX APIs.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Microsoft developed DirectX for game programmers and continues to add features to the API.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The DirectX specification is not controlled by an open arbitration committee and Microsoft is free to add, remove or change features.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Direct3D is not portable; it is designed specifically for Microsoft Windows and no other platform (though a form of Direct3D is used on Microsoft's Xbox, Windows Phone 7.5 smartphones and mobile devices which run the Pocket PC operating system).
[src:pygame/game-programming] Code written with OpenGL is easily ported between platforms with a compatible implementation.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, *Quake II*, which uses OpenGL, was ported from Windows to Linux by a fan of the game.
[src:pygame/game-programming] OpenGL is a standard maintained by the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (ARB).
[src:pygame/game-programming] The ARB meets periodically to update the standard by adding emerging support for features of the latest 3D hardware.
[src:pygame/game-programming] In addition, the development tools provided by the manufacturers of some video game consoles (such as the Nintendo GameCube, the Nintendo DS, and the PSP) use graphic APIs that resemble OpenGL.
[src:pygame/game-programming] OpenGL often lags behind on feature updates due to the lack of a permanent development team and the requirement that implementations begin development after the standard has been published.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Programmers who choose to use it can access some hardware's latest 3D features, but only through non-standardized extensions.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The situation may change in the future as the OpenGL architecture review board (ARB) has passed control of the specification to the Khronos Group in an attempt to counter the problem.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For development on Microsoft Windows, the various APIs of DirectX may be used for input, sound effects, music, networking and the playback of videos.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Many commercial libraries are available to accomplish these tasks, but since DirectX is available for free, it is the most widely used.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For console programming, the console manufacturers provide facilities for rendering graphics and the other tasks of game development.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The console manufacturers also provide complete development systems, without which one cannot legally market nor develop games for their system.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Third-party developers also sell toolkits or libraries that ease the development on one or more of these tasks or provide special benefits, such as cross-platform development capabilities.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The central component of any game, from a programming standpoint, is the *game loop*.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The game loop allows the game to run smoothly regardless of a user's input or lack thereof.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Most traditional software programs respond to user input and do nothing without it.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, a word processor formats words and text as a user types.
[src:pygame/game-programming] If the user doesn't type anything, the word processor does nothing.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some functions may take a long time to complete, but all are initiated by a user telling the program to do something.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Games, on the other hand, must continue to operate *regardless* of a user's input.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The loop may be refined and modified as game development progresses, but most games are based on this basic idea.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Game loops differ depending on the platform they are developed for.
[src:pygame/game-programming] For example, games written for DOS and many consoles can dominate and exploit available processing resources without restraint.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, games for a modern PC operating system such as Microsoft Windows must operate within the constraints of the process scheduler.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some modern games run multiple threads so that, for example, the computation of character AI can be decoupled from the generation of smooth motion within the game.
[src:pygame/game-programming] This has the disadvantage of (slightly) increased overhead, but the game may run more smoothly and efficiently on hyper-threading or multicore processors and on multiprocessor platforms.
[src:pygame/game-programming] With the computer industry's focus on CPUs with more cores that can execute more threads, this is becoming increasingly important.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Consoles like the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 already have more than one core per processor, and execute more than one thread per core.
[src:pygame/game-programming] The only platforms widely available for hobbyists to program are consumer operating systems, such as Android, iOS, Windows, Mac, Linux, etc.
[src:pygame/game-programming] This is because development on game consoles requires special development systems that cost thousands of dollars.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Often these must be obtained from the console manufacturer and are only sold or leased to professional game development studios.
[src:pygame/game-programming] However, Microsoft used to distribute a game development framework, XNA, which runs on both Microsoft Windows and Xbox 360.
[src:pygame/game-programming] XNA was discontinued, but other projects like MonoGame and SharpDX are trying to allow the same access for game coding.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some hobbyists also develop homebrew games, especially for handheld systems or modded consoles.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some software engineering students program games as exercises for learning a programming language or operating system.
[src:pygame/game-programming] Some hobbyists may use software packages that help with game development, such as Adobe Animate, Unity, Android Studio, pygame, Adventure Game Studio, Roblox Studio, GameMaker Studio, Godot, Unreal Engine, Pixel Game Maker MV, or Construct.
[src:pygame/pygame] Pygame was originally written by Pete Shinners to replace PySDL after its development stalled.
[src:pygame/pygame] It has been a community project since 2000 and is released under the free software GNU Lesser General Public License (which "provides for Pygame to be distributed with open source and commercial software").
[src:pygame/pygame] Pygame version 2 was planned as "Pygame Reloaded" in 2009, but development and maintenance of Pygame completely stopped until the end of 2016 with version 1.9.1.
[src:pygame/pygame] After the release of version 1.9.5 in March 2019, development of a new version 2 was active on the roadmap.
[src:pygame/pygame] Pygame 2.0 released on 28 October 2020, Pygame's 20th anniversary.
[src:pygame/pygame] Pygame uses the Simple DirectMedia Layer (SDL) library, with the intention of allowing real-time computer game development without the low-level mechanics of the C programming language and its derivatives.
[src:pygame/pygame] This is based on the assumption that the most expensive functions inside games can be abstracted from the game logic, making it possible to use a high-level programming language, such as Python, to structure the game.
[src:pygame/pygame] Other features that SDL does have include vector math, collision detection, 2D sprite scene graph management, MIDI support, camera, pixel-array manipulation, transformations, filtering, advanced freetype font support, and drawing.
[src:pygame/pygame] Applications using Pygame can run on Android phones and tablets with the use of Pygame Subset for Android (pgs4a).
[src:pygame/pygame] Sound, vibration, keyboard, and accelerometer are supported on Android.
[src:pygame/pygame] Following disagreements between former core developers and the repository owner, a fork known as pygame-ce (Community Edition) was created.
[src:pygame/pygame] There is a regular competition, called PyWeek, to write games using Python (and usually but not necessarily, Pygame).
[src:pygame/pygame] The community has created many tutorials for Pygame.
[src:pygame/pygame] The following code makes an image of a raccoon("raccoon.png") bounce when hitting an edge.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:pygame/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL manages video, audio, input devices, threads, shared object loading, computer networking and timers.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] For 3D graphics, it can handle an OpenGL, Vulkan, Metal, or Direct3D12 (older Direct3D versions 11 and 9 are also supported) context.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] A common misconception is that SDL is a game engine.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] However, the library is suited to building games directly, or is usable indirectly by engines built on top of it.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] The library is internally written in C and possibly, depending on the target platform, C++ or Objective-C, and provides the application programming interface in C, with bindings to other languages available.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] It is free and open-source software subject to the requirements of the zlib License since version 2.0, and with prior versions subject to the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Under the zlib License, SDL 2.0 is freely available for static linking in closed-source projects, unlike SDL 1.2, although it is possible for the user to override the statically linked library with one provided by them.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL 2.0, released in 2013, was a major departure from previous versions, offering more opportunity for 3D hardware acceleration, but breaking backwards-compatibility; a wrapper library made to translate 1.2 calls to 2.0 was later made available.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL is extensively used in the industry in both large and small projects.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] By 2010, over 700 games, 180 applications, and 120 demos had been posted on the library website.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL supports Emscripten (i.e. programs that run on a web page).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL 3 was released, as a stable version, in January 2025.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] It has a migration guide, and Coccinelle tool support to help migrate to the new major version.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL 3 has a new way to control the entry point of your program, and you can optionally control execution in a non-framework way.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Sam Lantinga created the library, first releasing it in early 1998, while working for Loki Software.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] He got the idea while porting a Windows application to Macintosh.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] He then used SDL to port *Doom* to BeOS (see Doom source ports).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Around the time of its creation, SDL was regarded as a simple alternative to DirectX.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Several other free libraries were developed to work alongside SDL, such as SMPEG and OpenAL.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] He also founded Galaxy Gameworks in 2008 to help commercially support SDL, although the company plans are currently on hold due to time constraints.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Soon after putting Galaxy Gameworks on hold, Lantinga announced that SDL 1.3 (which would then later become SDL 2.0) would be licensed under the zlib License.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Lantinga announced SDL 2.0 on 14 July 2012, at the same time announcing that he was joining Valve, the first version of which was announced the same day he joined the company.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Lantinga announced the stable release of SDL 2.0.0 on 13 August 2013.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL 2.0 is a major update to the SDL 1.2 codebase with a different, not backwards-compatible API.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] It replaces several parts of the 1.2 API with more general support for multiple input and output options.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Some feature additions include multiple window support, hardware-accelerated 2D graphics, and better Unicode support.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Support for Mir and Wayland was added in SDL 2.0.2 and enabled by default in SDL 2.0.4.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Version 2.0.4 also provided better support for Android.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] In 2024, the stable preview of SDL 3.1.3 was released (and in January 2025 3.2.0 was released as stable).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] It makes the API more consistent and allows access to more parts of the device, along with other features.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL is a wrapper around the operating-system-specific functions that the program needs to access.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] The only purpose of SDL is to provide a common framework for accessing these functions for multiple operating systems (cross-platform).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL provides support for 2D pixel operations, sound, file access, event handling, timing and threading.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] It is often used to complement OpenGL by setting up the graphical output and providing mouse and keyboard input, since OpenGL comprises only rendering.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] A game using the Simple DirectMedia Layer will *not* automatically run on every operating system; further adaptations must be applied.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] These are reduced to a minimum, since SDL also contains a few abstraction APIs for frequent functions offered by an operating system.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] The syntax of SDL is function-based: all operations done in SDL are done by passing parameters to subroutines (functions).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Special structures are also used to store the specific information SDL needs to handle.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL functions are categorized under several different subsystems.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Display and Window Management, surface functions, rendering acceleration, etc.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Besides this basic, low-level support, there also are a few separate official libraries that provide some more functions.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Other, non-standard libraries also exist.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] For example: SDL_Collide on SourceForge created by Amir Taaki.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Because of the way SDL is designed, much of its source code is split into separate modules for each operating system, to make calls to the underlying system.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] When SDL is compiled, the appropriate modules are selected for the target system.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] An unofficial Sixel back-end is available for SDL 1.2.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] The Rockbox MP3 player firmware also distributes a version of SDL 1.2, which is used to run games such as Quake.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Over the years SDL was used for many commercial and non-commercial video game projects.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] For instance, MobyGames listed 120 games using SDL in 2013, and the SDL website itself listed around 700 games in 2012.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Important commercial examples are *Angry Birds*, *Unreal Tournament*, and games developed using Valve's Source Engine, which uses SDL extensively for cross-platform compatibility; ones from the open-source domain are *OpenTTD*, *The Battle for Wesnoth* or *Freeciv*.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] The cross-platform game releases of the popular Humble Indie Bundles for Linux, Mac and Android are often SDL-based.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL is also often used for later ports on new platforms with legacy code.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] For instance, the PC game Homeworld was ported to the Pandora handheld and Jagged Alliance 2 for Android via SDL.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] Also, several non video game programs use SDL; examples are the emulators, such as DOSBox, FUSE ZX Spectrum emulator and VisualBoyAdvance.
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] There were several books written for development with SDL (see further reading).
[src:pygame/simple-directmedia-layer] SDL is used in university courses teaching multimedia and computer science, for instance, in a workshop about game programming using libSDL at the University of Cadiz in 2010, or a Game Design discipline at UTFPR (Ponta Grossa campus) in 2015.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:pygame/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
